tr 'A-Za-z' 'N-ZA-Mn-za-m'
This uses the tr command to perform character substitution:

'A-Za-z' specifies the input character set (all uppercase and lowercase letters)

'N-ZA-Mn-za-m' specifies the output mapping for ROT13:

A-Z becomes N-ZA-M (A→N, B→O, ..., M→Z, N→A, O→B, ..., Z→M)

a-z becomes n-za-m (same pattern for lowercase)

To create and test it:

bash
# Create the script
echo "tr 'A-Za-z' 'N-ZA-Mn-za-m'" > 15-rot13

# Make it executable
chmod +x 15-rot13

# Test with the provided example
echo '"Everyone is a proponent of strong encryption."
- Dorothy E. Denning' | ./15-rot13
The output should be:

text
"Rirelbar vf n cebcbarag bs fgebat rapelcgvba."
- Qbebgul R. Qraavat
To verify it works both ways (encoding and decoding):

bash
# Encode
echo "Hello World" | ./15-rot13
# Output: Uryyb Jbeyq

# Decode (same command)
echo "Uryyb Jbeyq" | ./15-rot13
# Output: Hello World
The script handles:

Uppercase and lowercase letters (A-Z, a-z)

Non-alphabetic characters remain unchanged

Works as both encoder and decoder (ROT13 property)

Processes standard input
